 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>DEAR SHAREHOLDERS:</FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Our
2012 annual meeting of shareholders will be held at the Hotel du Pont, 11th&nbsp;and Market Streets, Wilmington, Delaware, on Thursday, May&nbsp;10, 2012. The annual meeting will begin
promptly at 8:30&nbsp;a.m., Eastern Time. If you plan to attend the meeting, please see the instructions on page&nbsp;4. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Please
read these materials so that you'll know what we plan to do at the meeting. Also, please either sign and return the accompanying proxy card in the postage-paid envelope or
instruct us by telephone or via the Internet as to how you would like your shares voted. This way, your shares will be voted as you direct even if you can't attend the meeting. Instructions on
how to vote your shares by telephone or via the Internet are on the proxy card enclosed with this proxy statement. </FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:100%;margin-left:0%;">
<p style="font-family:times;"></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="cc47101_defined_terms"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_cc47101_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Defined Terms


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Annual Incentive Compensation Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> or </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Incentive Bonus Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's Annual Incentive
Compensation Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Class&nbsp;B Stock"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's Class&nbsp;B Stock. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Deferred Compensation Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's Deferred Compensation Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Dividend Equivalent"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means cash or shares of common stock (or common stock units) equal in value to dividends, if any, paid on shares of common stock. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Final Award"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means shares of common stock, Restricted Stock Units, and/or cash awarded by the Compensation Committee under a Performance Unit. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Ford"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> or </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"we"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> or </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Company"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford Motor Company. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Long-Term Incentive Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's 1998 or 2008 Long-Term Incentive Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Named Executives"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means the executives named in the Summary Compensation Table on p. 52. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"NYSE"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means the New York Stock Exchange,&nbsp;Inc. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Performance Unit"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means, under the Long-Term Incentive Plan, an award of the right to earn up to a certain number of shares of common
stock, Restricted Stock Units, or cash, or a combination of cash and shares of common stock or Restricted Stock Units, based on performance against specified goals established by the Compensation
Committee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Restricted Stock Unit"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means, under the Long-Term Incentive Plan, the right to receive a share of common stock, or cash equivalent to the
value of a share of common stock, when the restriction period ends, as determined by the Compensation Committee. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"SEC"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means the United States Securities and Exchange Commission. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"Senior Convertible Notes"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means the Ford Motor Company 4.25% Senior Convertible Notes due 2036 and the Ford Motor Company 4.25% Senior Convertible
Notes due 2016. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"1998 Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's 1998 Long-Term Incentive Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>"2008 Plan"</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> means Ford's 2008 Long-Term Incentive Plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>ii</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>

<A HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>
<IMG SRC="g1043079.jpg" ALT="GRAPHIC" WIDTH="162" HEIGHT="94">
  </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=5>Ford Motor Company </FONT></P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="20%" ALIGN="CENTER" -->
<HR NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="20%" ALIGN="CENTER" >


<A NAME="da47101_proxy_statement"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_1"> </A>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=3><B>Proxy Statement  </B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=3><B>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="20%" ALIGN="CENTER" -->
<HR NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="20%" ALIGN="CENTER" >


 </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Board of Directors is soliciting proxies to be used at the annual meeting of shareholders to be held on Thursday, May&nbsp;10, 2012, beginning at
8:30&nbsp;a.m., Eastern Time, at the Hotel du Pont, 11th&nbsp;and Market Streets, Wilmington, Delaware. This proxy statement and the enclosed form of proxy are being made available to shareholders
beginning March&nbsp;30, 2012. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_questions_and_answers_about_th__que02893"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS ABOUT THE PROXY MATERIALS AND THE ANNUAL MEETING


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_is_a_proxy_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_3"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What is a proxy?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A proxy is another person that you legally designate to vote your stock. If you designate someone as your proxy in a written document, that document
also is called a proxy or a proxy card. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_is_a_proxy_statement_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_4"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What is a proxy statement?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>It is a document that SEC regulations require that we make available to you when we ask you to vote your stock at the annual meeting. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_is_the_purpose_of_the_annual_meeting_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_5"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What is the purpose of the annual meeting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>At our annual meeting, shareholders will act upon the matters outlined in the notice of meeting, including the election of directors, ratification of
the selection of the Company's independent registered public accounting firm, a non-binding shareholder advisory vote to approve the compensation of the Named Executives, and consideration
of three shareholder proposals, if presented at the meeting. Also, management will report on the state of the Company and respond to questions from shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_is_the_record_date_and_what_does_it_mean_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_6"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What is the record date and what does it mean?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The record date for the annual meeting is March&nbsp;14, 2012. The record date is established by the Board of Directors as required by Delaware
law. Holders of common stock and holders of Class&nbsp;B Stock at the close of business on the record date are entitled to receive notice of the meeting and to vote at the meeting and any
adjournments or postponements of the meeting. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_who_is_entitled_to_vote_at_the_annual_meeting_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_7"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Who is entitled to vote at the annual meeting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Holders of common stock and holders of Class&nbsp;B Stock at the close of business on the record date may vote at the meeting. Holders of Senior
Convertible Notes cannot vote at this meeting. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>On
March&nbsp;14, 2012, 3,745,045,967 shares of common stock and 70,852,076 shares of Class&nbsp;B Stock were outstanding and, thus, are eligible to be voted. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>1</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=7,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=215493,FOLIO='1',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DA47101A.;14',USER='ABEAULI',CD='22-MAR-2012;21:08' -->
<A NAME="page_da47101_1_2"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_are_the_voting_rights_of___wha03058"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_8"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What are the voting rights of the holders of common stock and Class&nbsp;B Stock?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Holders of common stock and holders of Class&nbsp;B Stock will vote together without regard to class on the matters to be voted upon at the
meeting. Holders of common stock have 60% of the general voting power. Holders of Class&nbsp;B Stock have the remaining 40% of the general voting power. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each
outstanding share of common stock will be entitled to one vote on each matter to be voted upon. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
number of votes for each share of Class&nbsp;B Stock is calculated each year in accordance with the Company's Restated Certificate of Incorporation. At this year's meeting, each outstanding
share of Class&nbsp;B Stock will be entitled to 35.238 votes on each matter to be voted upon. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_is_the_difference_between__wha03188"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_9"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What is the difference between a shareholder of record and a "street name" holder?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If your shares are registered directly in your name with Computershare Trust Company, N.A., the Company's stock transfer agent, you are considered
the shareholder of record with respect to those shares. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
your shares are held in a stock brokerage account or by a bank or other nominee, you are considered the beneficial owner of these shares, and your shares are held in "street name." </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_how_do_i_vote_my_shares_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_10"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  How do I vote my shares?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If you are a shareholder of record, you can give a proxy to be voted at the meeting:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>over the telephone by calling a toll-free number; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>electronically, using the Internet; or </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>by mailing in a proxy card. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
telephone and Internet voting procedures have been set up for your convenience and have been designed to authenticate your identity, to allow you to give voting instructions, and to confirm that
those instructions have been recorded properly. If you are a shareholder of record and you would like to vote by telephone or the Internet, please refer to the specific instructions set forth on the
enclosed proxy card. If you wish to vote using a paper format and you return your signed proxy to us before the annual meeting, we will vote your shares as you direct. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
you are a Company employee or retiree participating in either of the Company's Savings and Stock Investment Plan for Salaried Employees or Tax-Efficient Savings Plan for Hourly
Employees, then you may be receiving this material because of shares held for you in those plans. In that case, you should follow the instructions from the plan trustee on how to vote those shares.
The trustee will vote the shares in accordance with your instructions and the terms of the plan. If you hold shares in any of these plans, the trustee will vote the shares held for you even if you do
not direct the trustee how to vote. In these cases, the trustee will vote any shares for which the trustee does not receive instructions in the same proportion as the trustee votes the shares for
which the trustee does receive instructions. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
you hold your shares in "street name," you must vote your shares in the manner prescribed by your broker or nominee. Your broker or nominee has enclosed, or explained how you can access, a voting
instruction card for you to use in directing the broker or nominee how to vote your shares. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_are_votes_confidential__who_counts_the_votes_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_11"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Are votes confidential? Who counts the votes?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The votes of all shareholders will be held in confidence from directors, officers and employees of the Company except: (a)&nbsp;as necessary to
meet applicable legal requirements and to assert or defend claims for or against the Company; (b)&nbsp;in case of a contested proxy solicitation; or (c)&nbsp;if a shareholder makes a written
comment on the proxy card or otherwise communicates his or her vote to management. We will also continue, as we have for many years, to retain an independent tabulator to receive and tabulate the
proxies and independent inspectors of election to certify the results. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>2</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=8,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=578328,FOLIO='2',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DA47101A.;14',USER='ABEAULI',CD='22-MAR-2012;21:08' -->
<A NAME="page_da47101_1_3"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_can_i_vote_my_shares_i__da402154"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_12"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Can I vote my shares in person at the annual meeting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Yes. If you are a shareholder of record, you may vote your shares at the meeting by completing a ballot at the meeting. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>However,
if you are a "street name" holder, you may vote your shares in person only if you obtain a signed proxy from your broker or nominee giving you the right to vote the shares. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
you hold shares in either of the Company's Savings and Stock Investment Plan for Salaried Employees or Tax-Efficient Savings Plan for Hourly Employees, you cannot vote at the meeting.
Your shares will be voted by the trustee of those plans as described on p. 2. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Even
if you currently plan to attend the meeting, we recommend that you also submit your proxy as described above so that your vote will be counted if you later decide not to attend the meeting. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_are_my_choices_when_voting_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_13"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What are my choices when voting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In the election of directors, you may vote for all nominees, or you may vote against one or more nominees. The proposal related to the election of
directors is described in this proxy statement beginning at p. 5. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
each of the other proposals, you may vote for the proposal, against the proposal, or abstain from voting on the proposal. These proposals are described in this proxy statement beginning at p. 69. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Proposals
1, 2, and 3 will be presented at the meeting by management, and the rest are expected to be presented by shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_are_the_board_s_recommendations_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_14"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What are the Board's recommendations?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Board of Directors recommends a vote </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> all of the nominees for director (Proposal 1), </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> ratifying the selection of
PricewaterhouseCoopers&nbsp;LLP as the Company's independent registered public accounting firm for 2012 (Proposal 2),
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> approval of the compensation of the Named Executives (Proposal 3), and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>AGAINST</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> the shareholder
proposals (Proposals 4 through 6). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_if_i_do_not_specify_how_i_want_my_shares_voted_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_15"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What if I do not specify how I want my shares voted?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If you do not specify on your proxy card (or when giving your proxy by telephone or the Internet) how you want to vote your shares, we will vote them </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> all of the nominees for director
(Proposal 1), </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> ratifying the selection of
PricewaterhouseCoopers&nbsp;LLP as the Company's independent registered public accounting firm for 2012 (Proposal 2), </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>FOR</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> approval of the compensation
of the Named Executives (Proposal 3), and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>AGAINST</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> the shareholder proposals (Proposals 4 through 6). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_can_i_change_my_vote_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_16"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Can I change my vote?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Yes. You can revoke your proxy at any time before it is exercised in any of three ways:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>by submitting written notice of revocation to the Secretary of the Company; </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>by submitting another proxy by telephone, via the Internet or by mail that is later dated and, if by mail, that is
properly signed; or </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>by voting in person at the meeting. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_what_percentage_of_the_vote_is__wha02835"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_17"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  What percentage of the vote is required for a proposal to be approved?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A majority of the votes that could be cast by shareholders who are either present in person or represented by proxy at the meeting is required to
elect the nominees for director and to approve each proposal. The votes are computed for each share as described on p. 2. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>3</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=9,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=419155,FOLIO='3',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DA47101A.;14',USER='ABEAULI',CD='22-MAR-2012;21:08' -->
<A NAME="page_da47101_1_4"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
total number of votes that could be cast at the meeting is the number of votes actually cast plus the number of abstentions. Abstentions are counted as "shares present" at the meeting for purposes
of determining whether a quorum exists and have the effect of a vote "against" any matter as to which they are specified. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Proxies
submitted by brokers that do not indicate a vote for some or all of the proposals because they don't have discretionary voting authority and haven't received instructions as to how to vote on
those proposals (so-called "broker non-votes") are not considered "shares present" and will not affect the outcome of the vote. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_how_can_i_attend_the_annual_meeting_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_18"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  How can I attend the annual meeting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If you are a shareholder of record and you plan to attend the annual meeting, please let us know by indicating in the appropriate place when you
return your proxy. Please tear off the top portion of your proxy card where indicated and bring it with you to the meeting. This portion of the card will serve as your ticket </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><I>and will admit you and one guest.</I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
you are a "street name" shareholder, tell your broker or nominee that you're planning to attend the meeting and would like a "legal proxy." Then simply bring that form to the meeting and we'll give
you a </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>ticket at the door that will admit you and one guest</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. If you can't get a legal proxy in time, we can still give you a ticket at the door if you
bring a copy of your brokerage account statement showing that you owned Ford stock as of the record date, March&nbsp;14, 2012. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_are_there_any_rules_regarding_admission_"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_19"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Are there any rules regarding admission?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each shareholder and guest will be asked to present valid government-issued picture identification, such as a driver's license or passport, before
being admitted to the meeting. Cameras and audio and video recording devices will not be permitted at the meeting and attendees will be subject to security inspections. We encourage you to leave any
such items at home. We will not be responsible for any items checked at the door. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="da47101_are_there_any_other_matters_to__are02677"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_da47101_20"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Are there any other matters to be acted upon at the annual meeting?


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We do not know of any other matters to be presented or acted upon at the meeting. Under our By-Laws, no business besides that stated in
the meeting notice may be transacted at any meeting of shareholders. If any other matter is presented at the meeting on which a vote may properly be taken, the shares represented by proxies will be
voted in accordance with the judgment of the person or persons voting those shares. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>4</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dc47101_election_of_directors_(proposal_1_on_the_proxy_card)"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dc47101_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Election of Directors<BR>  (Proposal&nbsp;1 on the Proxy Card)



</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Sixteen directors will be elected at this year's annual meeting. Each director will serve until the next annual meeting or until he
or she is succeeded by another qualified director who has been elected. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>William
Clay Ford, who had been a member of the Board of Directors since 1948, retired from the Board effective May&nbsp;12, 2005. As with previous years, the Board of Directors has again requested
that Mr.&nbsp;Ford serve as Director Emeritus so that the Board can continue to avail itself of his wisdom, judgment and experience, and Mr.&nbsp;Ford has agreed to so serve. Mr.&nbsp;Ford is
entitled to attend Board and committee meetings and participate in discussion of matters that come before the Board or its committees, although he is not entitled to vote upon any such matters and no
longer receives compensation as a non-employee Board member. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
will vote your shares as you specify when providing your proxy. If you do not specify how you want your shares voted when you provide your proxy, we will vote them </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>for the
election of all of the nominees listed below</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>. If unforeseen circumstances (such as death or disability) make it necessary for the Board of Directors to substitute another
person for any of the nominees, we will vote your shares for that other person. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dc47101_qualifications_considered_for_nominees"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dc47101_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Qualifications Considered for Nominees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Because Ford is a large and complex company, the Nominating and Governance Committee considers numerous qualifications when considering candidates
for the Board. Among the most important qualities directors should possess are the highest personal and professional ethical standards, integrity, and values. They should be committed to representing
the long-term interests of all of the shareholders. Directors must also have practical wisdom and mature judgment. Directors must be objective and inquisitive. Ford recognizes the value of
diversity and we endeavor to have a diverse Board, with experience in business, government, education and technology, and in areas that are relevant to the Company's global activities. Directors must
be willing to devote sufficient time to carrying out their duties and responsibilities effectively, and should be committed to serve on the Board for an extended period of time. Directors should also
be prepared to offer their resignation in the event of any significant change in their personal circumstances that could affect the discharge of their responsibilities as directors of the Company,
including a change in their principal job responsibilities. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each
of the nominees for director is now a member of the Board of Directors, which met nine times during 2011. Each of the nominees for director attended at least 75% of the combined Board of Director
and committee meetings held during the periods served by such nominee in 2011. The nominees provided the following information about themselves as of February&nbsp;1, 2012. Additionally, for each
director-nominee we have disclosed the particular experience, qualifications, attributes, or skills that led the Board to conclude that the nominee should serve as a director. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>5</FONT></P>

 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>6</FONT></P>

<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Anthony&nbsp;F. Earley, Jr.


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 62&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 2009 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal
Occupation:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Chairman, Chief Executive Officer&nbsp;&amp; President, PG&amp;E Corp., San Francisco, California </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Recent Business
Experience:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Mr.&nbsp;Earley became Chairman, Chief Executive Officer and President of PG&amp;E Corporation on September&nbsp;13, 2011. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Earley was Executive Chairman of DTE Energy since October 2010. He had
been Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of DTE Energy since 1998. Mr.&nbsp;Earley joined DTE Energy in 1994 as President and Chief Operating Officer. Prior to that time, Mr.&nbsp;Earley served as President and Chief Operating Officer of the Long
Island Lighting Company, an electric and gas utility in New&nbsp;York. Mr.&nbsp;Earley is a director of the Nuclear Energy Institute and the Edison Electric Institute. Mr.&nbsp;Earley also served as a director for several charitable organizations
including Cornerstone Schools, Detroit Zoological Society, Business Leaders for Michigan, and United Way for Southeastern Michigan. He also sits on the advisory board of the New&nbsp;York Stock Exchange and served as an officer in the United States
Navy nuclear submarine program where he was qualified as a chief engineer officer. Within the past five years, Mr.&nbsp;Earley served on the board of Comerica, Inc., and DTE Energy. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;">
<font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> PG&amp;E Corporation; Masco Corporation </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons
for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that, as Ford continues to develop hybrid and electric vehicles, Mr.&nbsp;Earley's experience as Chairman CEO and President of PG&amp;E Corp., his leadership positions in the electric and
nuclear industries, and his experience as a U.S. Navy officer, provide Ford with a uniquely qualified individual who can assist in the development of vehicles our customers want and value. In addition, Mr.&nbsp;Earley is able to provide valuable
advice regarding the development of the electrical infrastructure needed to assist in the widespread acceptance of electric vehicles. As the Chairman and CEO of PG&amp;E Corp., and formerly at DTE Energy, Mr.&nbsp;Earley also possesses significant
leadership and general management expertise.</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

a retired Vice President of Ford Motor Company and former President and Chief Operating Officer of Ford Motor Credit Company. He presently serves as a consultant to the Company. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font
size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> International Speedway Corporation </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for

deliberations. Mr.&nbsp;Ford also adds significant value in various stakeholder relationships, including relationships with dealers, non-government organizations, employees, and the communities in which Ford has a significant presence.
Mr.&nbsp;Ford's life-long affiliation with the Company provides the Board with a unique historical perspective and a focus on the long-term interests of the Company.</FONT></TD>

 William Clay Ford, Jr.

<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 54&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 1988 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal

Experience:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Mr.&nbsp;Ford has held a number of management positions within Ford, including Vice President&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;Commercial Truck Vehicle Center. From 1995 until October&nbsp;30, 2001, Mr.&nbsp;Ford was Chair of the
Finance Committee. Effective January&nbsp;1, 1999, he was elected Chairman of the Board of Directors and effective October&nbsp;30, 2001, he was elected Chief Executive Officer of the Company. Mr.&nbsp;Ford became Executive Chairman of the Company on
September&nbsp;1, 2006 and is the current Chair of the Finance Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Ford also is Vice Chairman of The Detroit Lions, Inc., Chairman of the Detroit Economic Club, and Trustee of The Henry Ford. He also is a member of the Boards of
Business Leaders for Michigan and the Henry Ford Health System. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> eBay&nbsp;Inc. </font>
<p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that Mr.&nbsp;Ford's extensive experience in various executive positions, service as CEO,
and present service as Executive Chairman, provides the Board with unique insight regarding Company-wide issues. This experience, as well as in his role as Chairman of the Board, assist the Board in developing its long-term strategy, while his
life-long affiliation with the Company reinforces the long-term interests of Ford and its shareholders. Mr.&nbsp;Ford's knowledge and experience also add significant value to the Company's relationship with its various stakeholders.</FONT></TD>

 Richard&nbsp;A. Gephardt

<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 71&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 2009 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal

of DLA Piper, one of the world's largest legal services providers, and as a consultant to Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. Mr.&nbsp;Gephardt is the former Majority Leader of the U.S. House of Representatives and served 14&nbsp;terms in Congress from
1976 until January 2005. While in Congress, he served on the Budget Committee and on the Ways and Means Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Gephardt was elected Chairman of the House Democratic Caucus in 1984; and he served as majority leader from 1989 to 1994. In
1994, he was elected House Democratic Leader, the top Democratic leadership position in the House. Mr.&nbsp;Gephardt also served as minority leader from 1995 to 2003. Within the past five years, Mr.&nbsp;Gephardt served on the board of Dana Holding
Corporation. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Centene Corporation; CenturyLink; Spirit Aerosystems Holding,

distinguished career in public service provides the Board with important insight into the many government relations and international issues affecting Ford. Additionally, Mr.&nbsp;Gephardt's experience in business consulting provides Ford with unique
knowledge of business challenges across a broad spectrum of industries.</FONT></TD>

officer and former vice chairman of Bank of America, where he retired in 2005 after 18&nbsp;years with the company. A certified public accountant, Mr.&nbsp;Hance spent 17&nbsp;years with Price Waterhouse (now PricewaterhouseCoopers) in Philadelphia
and Charlotte. From August 1985 until December 1986, he was chairman and co-owner of Consolidated Coin Caterers Corp. In March 1987, Mr.&nbsp;Hance joined NCNB, a predecessor to Bank of America. Mr.&nbsp;Hance also is a trustee of Washington
University in St.&nbsp;Louis and Johnson&nbsp;&amp; Wales University, based in Providence, R.I. Mr.&nbsp;Hance is the non-Executive Chairman of the Board of Sprint Nextel Corp. and a senior advisor to the Carlyle Group. Within the past five years,
Mr.&nbsp;Hance served on the boards of Rayonier, Inc. and EnPro Industries, Inc. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Sprint

that Mr.&nbsp;Hance's extensive experience in the banking industry brings financial expertise to deliberations regarding the Company's balance sheet and liquidity. In addition, Mr.&nbsp;Hance's CPA background, his experience as a Chief Financial
Officer, and his tenure as vice chairman of Bank of America, provide the Board with another experienced point of view in accounting, Audit Committee, and general operational matters.</FONT></TD>

<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Richard&nbsp;A. Manoogian


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 75&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 2001 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal
Occupation:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Chairman of the Board, Masco Corporation, Taylor, Michigan </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Recent Business Experience:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian has been with Masco since 1958, became Vice President and a member of the Board in 1964, President in 1968, and Chairman in 1985. Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian served as Chief Executive Officer of Masco from 1985 until he transitioned to
Executive Chairman in July 2007. Effective June&nbsp;30, 2009, Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian retired from the position of Executive Chairman of Masco. Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian is a member of the Board of Business Leaders for Michigan, The Henry Ford, and the Detroit
Economic Club. Within the past five years, Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian served on the Board of JPMorgan Chase&nbsp;&amp; Co. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company
Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Masco Corporation </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian's
experience as Chairman and CEO of Masco provides the Board with overall general management expertise as well as experience in the successful development of multiple brands. Additionally, as an experienced CEO of a </FONT><FONT
SIZE=2><I>S&amp;P&nbsp;500</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> company, Mr.&nbsp;Manoogian brings a wealth of knowledge on executive compensation matters to his position as Chair of the Compensation Committee.</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

 Ellen&nbsp;R. Marram

 </B></FONT><BR>

Occupation:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> President, The Barnegat Group, LLC </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Recent Business Experience:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> Ms.&nbsp;Marram is
President of the Barnegat Group, LLC, a business advisory firm. From September 2000 through December 2005, Ms.&nbsp;Marram was Managing Director of North Castle Partners, LLC, a private equity firm. Ms.&nbsp;Marram previously served as President and
CEO of Tropicana Beverage Group from September 1997 until November 1998, and had previously served as President of the Group, as well as Executive Vice President of The Seagram Company Ltd. and Joseph&nbsp;E. Seagram&nbsp;&amp; Sons, Inc. Before
joining Seagram in 1993, she served as President and CEO of Nabisco Biscuit Company and Senior Vice President of the Nabisco Foods Group from June 1988 until April 1993. Ms.&nbsp;Marram also is a member of the North American Advisory Board of
Deutsche Bank. She is a trustee of Wellesley College and serves on a number of non-profit boards, including Institute for the Future, New&nbsp;York Presbyterian Hospital, and the Lincoln Center Theater. Within the past five years, Ms.&nbsp;Marram
served on the board of Cadbury Schweppes plc. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The New&nbsp;York Times Company; Eli
Lilly and Company </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that Ms.&nbsp;Marram's general management and marketing
experience in managing well-known consumer brands adds significant expertise to Ford's focus on strengthening our core brands. Additionally, Ms.&nbsp;Marram's experience in advising companies provides her with multiple perspectives on successful
strategies across a variety of businesses. Ms.&nbsp;Marram also brings a keen understanding of corporate governance matters to her position as Chair of the Nominating and Governance Committee.</FONT></TD>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Alan Mulally


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 66&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 2006 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal
Occupation:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> President and Chief Executive Officer, Ford Motor Company </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Recent Business Experience:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
Mr.&nbsp;Mulally was elected President and Chief Executive Officer of Ford effective September&nbsp;1, 2006. Since March 2001, Mr.&nbsp;Mulally had been Executive Vice President of the Boeing Company and President and Chief Executive Officer of
Boeing Commercial Airplanes. He also was a member of the Boeing Executive Council. Prior to that time, Mr.&nbsp;Mulally served as President of Boeing's space and defense business. Mr.&nbsp;Mulally has served as co-chair of the Washington
Competitiveness Council, and has sat on the advisory boards of NASA, the University of Washington, the University of Kansas, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and the U.S. Air Force Scientific Advisory Board. He is a member of the U.S.
National Academy of Engineering and a fellow of England's Royal Academy of Engineering. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> As Ford's
President and CEO, the Board believes that Mr.&nbsp;Mulally continues to provide the strategic and management leadership necessary to create an exciting viable Ford delivering profitable growth for all. Mr.&nbsp;Mulally's experience at Boeing after
September&nbsp;11, 2001, evidenced his expertise in managing a company in the midst of a crisis by focusing its management on important business priorities, leading to a period of sustained growth. Mr.&nbsp;Mulally continues to use these skills to
lead Ford in executing our ONE Ford Plan.</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

Physics, Interim President Emeritus and Vice President for Research Emeritus at the University of Michigan. He joined the University as Chairman of its Physics Department in 1987 and in 1993 was named Vice President of Research. Dr.&nbsp;Neal served
as Interim President of the University of Michigan from July&nbsp;1, 1996 to February&nbsp;1, 1997. He has served as a member of the U.S. National Science Board, the Advisory Board of the Oak Ridge National Laboratory, as a Trustee of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies and as a member of the Board of Regents of the Smithsonian Institution. Dr.&nbsp;Neal currently is a member of the Board of Trustees of the Richard Lounsbery Foundation and a member of the Advisory Board for the
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. He is also a member of the Board of Physics and Astronomy of the National Academy of Sciences and a member of the Council of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture. </font> <p
align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that Dr.&nbsp;Neal's vast experience and knowledge in the field of science brings a unique
skill to the Board. Dr.&nbsp;Neal's expertise has assisted our intellectual property management process through his presence on the Ford Board of Directors and on the board of managers of Ford Global Technologies, LLC. Additionally, as Chair of the
Sustainability Committee, he continues to apply his unique scientific knowledge to the development and implementation of Ford's long-term sustainability strategy.</FONT></TD>

 Gerald&nbsp;L. Shaheen

 </B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2><I>Age:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 67&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Director Since:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 2007 </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Principal

Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen was appointed Group President of Caterpillar in November 1998 and had responsibility for the design, development and production of the company's large construction and mining equipment, as well as marketing and sales operations in
North America, Caterpillar's components business, and its research and development division. Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen joined Caterpillar in 1967 and held a variety of management positions. Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen retired from Caterpillar effective February&nbsp;1,
2008. Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen is a board member and past chairman of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, a board member of the MS Society of Greater Illinois, Chairman of the Illinois Neurological Institute, and Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Bradley
University. Within the past five years, Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen served on the board of National City Corporation. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Current Public Company
Directorships:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> AGCO Corporation </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Reasons for Nomination:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> The Board believes that Mr.&nbsp;Shaheen's
extensive experience as a Group President at Caterpillar adds a depth of manufacturing and general management knowledge that is beneficial for an automobile manufacturer. His knowledge of marketing and sales, as well as experience in research and
development, related to the manufacture and sale of products in a capital and labor intensive industry, provide valuable insight into Ford's efforts to build products our customers want and value.</FONT></TD>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="de47101_committees_of_the_board_of_directors"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_de47101_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Committees of the Board of Directors


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:100%;margin-left:0%;">
<p style="font-family:times;"></FONT></P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"100%" -->

<!-- User-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER"><TABLE width="100%"  BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>
<TR><!-- TABLE COLUMN WIDTHS SET -->
<TD WIDTH="178pt" style="font-family:times;"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="12pt" style="font-family:times;"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="" style="font-family:times;"></TD>
<!-- TABLE COLUMN WIDTHS END --></TR>

<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Audit Committee


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Number of Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 5<BR></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Stephen&nbsp;G. Butler </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>(Chair)</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kimberly&nbsp;A. Casiano<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James&nbsp;H. Hance, Jr.<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Irvine&nbsp;O. Hockaday, Jr.<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gerald&nbsp;L. Shaheen </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Number of Meetings in 2011:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 11</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Functions:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
Selects the independent registered public accounting firm to audit Ford's books and records, subject to shareholder ratification, and determines the compensation of the independent registered public accounting firm. </font> <p align=left
style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> At least annually, reviews a report by the independent registered public accounting firm describing: internal quality control procedures, any issues raised by an internal or peer quality control
review, any issues raised by a governmental or professional authority investigation in the past five years and any steps taken to deal with such issues, and (to assess the independence of the independent registered public accounting firm) all
relationships between the independent registered public accounting firm and the Company. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Consults with the independent registered public accounting firm, reviews and
approves the scope of their audit, and reviews their independence and performance. Also, annually approves of categories of services to be performed by the independent registered public accounting firm and reviews and, if appropriate, approves in
advance any new proposed engagement greater than $250,000. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews internal controls, accounting practices, and financial reporting, including the results of the annual
audit and the review of the interim financial statements with management and the independent registered public accounting firm. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews activities, organization structure,
and qualifications of the General Auditor's Office, and participates in the appointment, dismissal, evaluation, and the determination of the compensation of the General Auditor. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font
size=2> Discusses earnings releases and guidance provided to the public and rating agencies. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Review, at least annually, policies with respect to risk assessment and risk
management. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews, with the Office of the General Counsel, any legal or regulatory matter that could have a significant impact on the financial statements. </font> <p
align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> As appropriate, obtains advice and assistance from outside legal, accounting or other advisors. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Prepares
an annual report of the Audit Committee to be included in the Company's proxy statement. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Assesses annually the adequacy of the Audit Committee Charter. </font> <p
align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reports to the Board of Directors about these matters.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<!-- end of user-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>14</FONT></P>

<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD COLSPAN=3 style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Compensation Committee


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Number of Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 4<BR></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Richard&nbsp;A.&nbsp;Manoogian&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>(Chair)</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Anthony&nbsp;F. Earley, Jr.<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ellen&nbsp;R. Marram<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;John&nbsp;L. Thornton </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Number of Meetings in 2011:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;8</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Functions:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
Establishes and reviews the overall executive compensation philosophy and strategy of the Company. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews and approves Company goals and objectives related to the
Executive Chairman and the President and CEO and other executive officer compensation, including annual performance objectives. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Evaluates the performance of the Executive
Chairman and the President and CEO and other executive officers in light of established goals and objectives and, based on such evaluation, reviews and approves the annual salary, bonus, stock options, Performance Units, other stock-based awards,
other incentive awards and other benefits, direct and indirect, of the Executive Chairman and the President and CEO and other executive officers. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Conducts a risk assessment
of the Company's compensation policies and practices. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Considers and makes recommendations on Ford's executive compensation plans and programs. </font> <p align=left
style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews the Compensation Discussion and Analysis to be included in the Company's proxy statement. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Prepares an annual
report of the Compensation Committee to be included in the Company's proxy statement. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Assesses annually the adequacy of the Compensation Committee Charter.<BR>
</font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reports to the Board of Directors about these matters.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Finance Committee


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Number of Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 7<BR></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;William&nbsp;Clay&nbsp;Ford,&nbsp;Jr.&nbsp;</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>(Chair)</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Edsel&nbsp;B. Ford II<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;James&nbsp;H. Hance, Jr.<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;William&nbsp;W. Helman IV<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Alan Mulally<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Homer&nbsp;A. Neal<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;John&nbsp;L. Thornton </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Number of Meetings in 2011:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;5</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><BR>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><BR><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Functions:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
Reviews all aspects of the Company's policies and practices that relate to the management of the Company's financial affairs, not inconsistent, however, with law or with specific instructions given by the Board of Directors relating to such matters.
</font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews with management, at least annually, the Annual Report from the Treasurer of the Company's cash and funding plans and other Treasury matters. </font> <p align=left
style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reviews the strategy and performance of the Company's pension and other retirement and savings plans. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Performs such
other functions and exercises such other powers as may be delegated to it by the Board of Directors from time to time. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Review, at least annually, policies with respect to
financial risk assessment and financial risk management. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Assesses annually the adequacy of the Finance Committee Charter. </font> <p align=left
style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reports to the Board of Directors about these matters.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

 Nominating and Governance Committee


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT></TD>

<TD style="font-family:times;"><p style="font-family:times;margin-top:12pt;margin-left:0pt;"><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Number of Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> 12<BR></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Members:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>

<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;<BR></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>Functions:</I></B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><BR>
Reviews and makes recommendations on: </FONT><FONT SIZE=2> </font><p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:-12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> &#149; </font></p> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:10pt;"> <font size=2> </FONT><FONT
SIZE=2>the nominations or elections of directors; and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>  </font><p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:-12pt;margin-left:0pt;"> &#149; </font></p> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:0pt;margin-left:10pt;"> <font size=2>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=2>the size, composition, and compensation of the Board.<BR>
</font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Establishes criteria for selecting new directors and the evaluation of the Board. Develops and recommends to the Board corporate governance principles and guidelines.
Reviews the charter and composition of each committee of the Board and makes recommendations to the Board for the adoption of or revisions to the committee charters, the creation of additional committees, or the elimination of committees. </font> <p
align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Considers the adequacy of the By-Laws and the Restated Certificate of Incorporation of the Company and recommends to the Board, as appropriate, that the Board: (i)&nbsp;adopt
amendments to the By-Laws, and (ii)&nbsp;propose, for consideration by the shareholders, amendments to the Restated Certificate of Incorporation. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Considers shareholder
suggestions for nominees for director (other than self-nominations). See Corporate Governance on p.&nbsp;19. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Assesses annually the adequacy of the Nominating and Governance
Committee Charter. </font> <p align=left style="font-family:times;margin-top:11pt;margin-left:0pt;"> <font size=2> Reports to the Board of Directors about these matters.</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dg47101_audit_committee_report"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dg47101_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Audit Committee Report


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Audit Committee is composed of five directors, all of whom meet the independence standards contained in the NYSE Listed Company
rules, SEC rules and Ford's Corporate Governance Principles, and operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors. A copy of the Audit Committee Charter may be found on the Company's
website, <U>www.corporate.ford.com</U>. The Audit Committee selects, subject to shareholder ratification, the Company's independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Ford
management is responsible for the Company's internal controls and the financial reporting process. The independent registered public accounting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers&nbsp;LLP
("PricewaterhouseCoopers"), is responsible for performing independent audits of the Company's consolidated financial statements and internal controls over financial reporting and issuing an opinion on
the conformity of those audited financial statements with United States generally accepted accounting principles and on the effectiveness of the Company's internal controls
over financial reporting. The Audit Committee monitors the Company's financial reporting process and reports to the Board of Directors on its findings. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


Audit Fees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company paid PricewaterhouseCoopers $35.7&nbsp;million and $35.9&nbsp;million for audit services for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2011
and 2010, respectively. Audit services consisted of the audit of the financial statements included in the Company's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K, reviews of the financial statements
included in the Company's Quarterly Reports on Form&nbsp;10-Q, attestation of the effectiveness of the Company's internal controls over financial reporting, preparation of statutory
audit reports, and providing comfort letters in connection with Ford and Ford Motor Credit Company funding transactions. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


Audit-Related Fees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company paid PricewaterhouseCoopers $6.6&nbsp;million and $5.4&nbsp;million for audit-related services for the years ended
December&nbsp;31, 2011 and 2010, respectively. Audit-related services included support of funding transactions, due diligence for mergers, acquisitions and divestitures, employee benefit plan
audits, attestation services, internal control reviews, and assistance with interpretation of accounting standards. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


Tax Fees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company paid PricewaterhouseCoopers $4.4&nbsp;million and $3.6&nbsp;million for tax services for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 and
2010, respectively. The types of tax services provided included assistance with tax compliance and the preparation of tax returns, tax consultation, planning and implementation
services, assistance in connection with tax audits, and tax advice related to mergers, acquisitions and divestitures. Of the fees paid for tax services, the Company paid 53% and 72% for tax compliance
and the preparation of Company tax returns in 2011 and 2010, respectively. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


All Other Fees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company paid PricewaterhouseCoopers $0.5&nbsp;million for other services for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011. The types of other
services provided included advisory services to help support quantification of potential insurance claims and research analysis regarding new markets. The Company did not engage PricewaterhouseCoopers
for any other services for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2010. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>



<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


Total Fees


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company paid PricewaterhouseCoopers a total of $47.2 and $44.9&nbsp;million in fees for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 and 2010,
respectively. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>17</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=23,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=293558,FOLIO='17',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DG47101A.;7',USER='SLYUBOM',CD='20-MAR-2012;19:53' -->
<A NAME="page_dg47101_1_18"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


Auditor Independence


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>During the last year, the Audit Committee met and held discussions with management and PricewaterhouseCoopers. The Audit Committee reviewed and
discussed with Ford management and PricewaterhouseCoopers the audited financial statements and the assessment of the effectiveness of internal controls over financial reporting contained in the
Company's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011. The Audit Committee also discussed with PricewaterhouseCoopers the matters required to be discussed
by applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board regarding the independent registered public accounting firm's communications with the Audit Committee concerning
independence, as well as by SEC regulations. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>PricewaterhouseCoopers
submitted to the Audit Committee the written disclosures and the letter required by applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board regarding the
independent registered public accounting firm's communications with the audit committee concerning independence. The Audit Committee discussed with PricewaterhouseCoopers such firm's independence. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Based
on the reviews and discussions referred to above, the Audit Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the audited financial statements be included in the Company's Annual Report on
Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011, filed with the SEC. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Audit Committee also considered whether the provision of other non-audit services by PricewaterhouseCoopers to the Company is compatible with maintaining the independence of
PricewaterhouseCoopers and concluded that the independence of PricewaterhouseCoopers is not compromised by the provision of such services. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Annually,
the Audit Committee pre-approves categories of services to be performed (rather than individual engagements) by PricewaterhouseCoopers. As part of this approval, an amount is
established for each category of services (Audit, Audit-Related, and Tax Services). In the event the pre-approved amounts prove to be insufficient, a request for incremental funding will
be submitted to the Audit Committee for approval during the next regularly scheduled meeting. In addition, all new engagements greater than $250,000 will be presented in advance to the Audit Committee
for approval. A regular report is prepared for each regular Audit Committee meeting outlining actual fees and expenses paid or committed against approved fees. </FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:100%;margin-left:0%;">
<p style="font-family:times;"></FONT></P>

 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>18</FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>
