Gamble is typically included in our survey group; however, it did not meet the timing requirements to be included in the Towers Watson survey results this year. </FONT></P>
 </DIV>
 <P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>37</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=43,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=390788,FOLIO='37',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DM47101A.;45',USER='EYOUNG',CD='26-MAR-2012;08:15' -->
<A NAME="page_dm47101_1_38"> </A>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>While
the Committee uses the survey data as a reference point, it is not, and was not in 2011, the sole determining factor in executive compensation decisions. We generally seek to provide total
compensation opportunities at or around the survey group's median total compensation. Consistent with our compensation Guiding Principles discussed above, we incorporate flexibility into our
compensation programs to respond to, and adjust for, changes in the business/economic environment and individual accomplishments, performance and circumstances. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
survey did not yield results on Mr.&nbsp;Ford's position and, consequently, his compensation was excluded from our analysis of how the total direct compensation of our Named Executives compares
to that of the survey group. The 2011 survey results indicated that the actual total direct compensation for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally was significantly above the median; for Messrs.&nbsp;Booth and Fields,
total direct compensation was above the median; and for Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs, total direct compensation was approximately at the median. Because we overachieved for our Incentive Bonus Plan for 2010
performance, actual cash compensation for the Named Executives was above the median of the survey group. Also, equity-based compensation was below the median on average, except for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally,
whose equity-based compensation was above the median (see Equity-Based Compensation on pp.&nbsp;45-47 for a discussion of how equity compensation affected the compensation of the Named Executives). </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>An
analysis of how each element of compensation listed below compared to the survey data for 2011, as well as how the factors described above, including the competitive survey data review, affected
Named Executive compensation decisions during 2011, is included in the discussion of each element. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


D.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Internal Pay Equity and Equity-Value Accumulation Analyses


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each year, the Committee reviews the amount of all components of compensation of our executive officers. This review includes data on salary, annual bonuses, and equity-based
awards, as well as qualitative data on perquisites. The Committee also takes into account relative pay considerations within the officer group and data covering individual performance. The Committee
uses this analysis to assist it in ensuring internal equity among the executive officer group. The Committee did not take any actions related to the Named Executives in 2011 as a result of this
analysis. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee also considers the potential value of outstanding equity grants and uses this information as one data-point in evaluating equity compensation grants. For instance, the
Committee reviewed the value of equity-based awards at certain price levels of Ford stock. The analysis included the following:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>"in-the-money" stock options; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>unvested Restricted Stock Units; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>2011 Performance Unit grant; and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>2011 Incremental Incentive Grants. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee uses this analysis to evaluate the accumulated wealth and retention value in equity of the Named Executives in light of the Company's change in market value. Given our performance during
the past three years, the Committee believes our equity-based incentive programs are appropriate to attract, motivate and retain executives, as well as incentivize executives to accomplish our ONE
Ford objectives. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>38</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A> </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


E.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Management Recommendations


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Committee considers recommendations from Mr.&nbsp;Ford, Mr.&nbsp;Mulally, and the Group Vice President&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;Human Resources and
Corporate Services, in developing compensation plans and evaluating performance of other executive officers. The Committee's consultant also provides advice and analyses on the structure and level of
executive compensation (see Compensation Committee Operations on p&nbsp;25). As noted in How We Determine Compensation&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;B.&nbsp;ONE Ford above,
Mr.&nbsp;Mulally established the ONE Ford corporate priorities. Our senior leadership team developed the 2011 business plan metrics and targets to support our ONE Ford priorities. Our Human
Resources and Finance departments developed the incentive plan performance weightings and targets in support of the business plan and ONE Ford. Final decisions on the design of our incentive plans and
any major element of compensation, however, as well as total compensation for each executive officer, were made by the Compensation Committee. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="do47101_what_we_pay_and_why_we_pay_it"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_do47101_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GUTTERGRID,"border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;" -->


&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<!-- end of user-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each
compensation element is aligned with the Philosophy, Strategy and Guiding Principles discussed on pp.&nbsp;35-36. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>To
achieve our objectives and to support our business strategy, compensation paid to our executives is structured to ensure that there is an appropriate balance among the various forms of
compensation. The Committee attempts to strike appropriate balances by analyzing the competitive market for executive talent, our business results and forecasts, and our key strategic goals for the
year. The charts below show the various balances we achieved among </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>39</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=45,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=198408,FOLIO='39',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DO47101A.;70',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='23-MAR-2012;15:44' -->
<A NAME="page_do47101_1_40"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>our
executive officer group (with and without any incremental equity grants) compared to the balances achieved by the survey group: </FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:100%;margin-left:0%;">
<p style="font-family:times;"></FONT></P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"100%" -->

<!-- User-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER"><TABLE width="100%"  BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>

<TD WIDTH="48%" style="font-family:times;"></TD>
<!-- TABLE COLUMN WIDTHS END --></TR>

<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


 Ford&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </B></FONT></TD>
<TD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>As the charts indicate, cash compensation makes up a higher percentage of our executives' compensation than that of the comparator group's median whether or not any incremental
equity grants are included (see 2011 Incremental Incentive Grants on p.&nbsp;47). This result is primarily due to: (i)&nbsp;the salaries for the Named Executives are above the median of the survey
group; and (ii)&nbsp;the 2010 Incentive Bonus Plan payouts were higher than the 2010 targets because of our exceptional performance against metrics for the 2010 performance year. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="do47101_annual_compensation"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_do47101_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Annual Compensation


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Annual compensation for our executives includes salary and cash incentive bonus, if earned, paid in cash. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Salaries


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>When considering increases to base salaries, the Compensation Committee takes into account the following factors:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>the individual's job duties, performance and achievements; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>similar positions of responsibility within the Company (internal pay equity); </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>job tenure, time since last salary increase, retention concerns and critical skills; and </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>level of pay compared to comparable positions at companies in the survey group. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Compensation Committee reviews salaries of the Named Executives annually and at the time of a promotion or other major change in responsibilities. Our competitive survey results for 2010 indicated
that salaries were competitive for our salaried personnel, including the Named Executives. In light of this analysis and as part of our objective to control costs, there were no increases to salaries
(annual merit or otherwise) for any of the Named Executives in 2011. Messrs.&nbsp;Ford and Mulally voluntarily reduced their salaries for 2009 and 2010; their salaries returned to the 2008 level at
$2&nbsp;million per year effective January&nbsp;1, 2011. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>40</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=46,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=98954,FOLIO='40',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DO47101A.;70',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='23-MAR-2012;15:44' -->
<A NAME="page_do47101_1_41"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Throughout
2011, the salaries for the Named Executives were above the median of the survey group. We believe that paying base salaries at the high end of the competitive survey is appropriate to
retain executives throughout the business cycle because cash compensation and/or total compensation may be much lower than competitive levels at certain times during the business cycle (see
Competitive Survey on pp.&nbsp;37-38). The relative salary level is also explained by the fact that Ford is generally larger and more complex than many of the companies in the survey group, with
world-wide operations, and a capital intensive business involving complex products with long product development timelines. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Incentive Bonuses


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Because of our improved performance over the 3-year to 5-year periods, the Committee decided to maintain the current structure of our Incentive Bonus
Plan for the 2011 performance period. The metrics and weightings under our Incentive Bonus Plan further our ONE Ford Plan by incentivizing executives to accomplish key metrics and promote teamwork
across the global organization. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
2011, for Named Executives whose primary responsibilities involved a particular business unit, the Committee set a formula that was based on the following metrics (weighting of each metric in
parenthesis):</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>global profits-before-taxes (PBT) (35%); </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>global Automotive operating-related cash flow (35%);* </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>relevant business unit cost performance (10%); </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>relevant business unit market share (10%); and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>relevant business unit quality (10%). </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee determined that this structure best took into account Company as well as individual performance for those Named Executives responsible for specific business units. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Those
Named Executives whose duties are of a global nature were placed in the "Corporate" business unit. For these executives, the performance metrics used for 2011 were the following (weighting of
each metric in parenthesis):</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>global PBT (35%); </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>global Automotive operating-related cash flow (35%);* </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>total cost performance (10%); </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>a weighted average of all business unit market share performance (10%); and </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>a weighted average of all business unit quality performance (10%). </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="12%" ALIGN="LEFT" -->
<HR NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="12%" ALIGN="LEFT" >


<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>*</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
define total Automotive operating-related cash flow as automotive pre-tax profits (excluding special items as detailed in Ford's Annual Report
on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011) adjusted for the following:</FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>less: capital spending (additional cash outflow); </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>add back: depreciation and amortization (non-cash expense); </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>add/deduct: changes in receivables, inventory, and trade payables; and </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>other&nbsp;&#151; primarily expense and timing differences. </FONT></DD></DL>
</DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
following are excluded in the calculation of total Automotive operating-related cash flow:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>pension plan contributions; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>employee separation payments; and</FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>tax payments from affiliates. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>41</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>

<A NAME="page_do47101_1_42"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A

 <!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="12%" ALIGN="LEFT" -->
<HR NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="12%" ALIGN="LEFT" >


<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>*</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
2006, the Committee established targets for executive officers based on the individual's level of responsibility, competitive compensation data, pay equity
considerations among the executive officers, past target amounts, as well as the need for flexibility to motivate and reward exceptional performance while maximizing the deductibility of compensation
by following the shareholder approved terms of the Incentive Bonus Plan. When Mr.&nbsp;Mulally joined Ford in 2006, the Committee agreed that his 2007 Incentive Bonus Plan target would be 175% of
his salary of $2&nbsp;million. The bonus target for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally is above the Survey group's median while the targets for Messrs.&nbsp;Booth, Fields, and Hinrichs are at the survey group's
median.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>**</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
2008, the Committee reduced Mr.&nbsp;Ford's Incentive Bonus target from 175% of salary to $1&nbsp;million and increased his equity-based compensation
target. The Committee believes this arrangement is more appropriate for the position of Executive Chairman and focuses his efforts on long-term objectives. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amount earned under the Incentive Bonus Plan was determined pursuant to a pre-established sliding scale, based on various levels of achievement for each metric. If minimum performance
levels had not been met for all metrics, the payout would have been zero. The maximum extent to which a performance metric could be achieved was 200% of the target. The Committee believes that a scale
which allows a maximum award of 200% of target incentivizes executive behavior to exceed business objectives. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
the business units in which Named Executives participated, the following table shows the performance metric, the target, and the performance results for 2011. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>42</FONT></P>

  2011 Incentive Bonus Target and Performance Results

  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

&nbsp;</B></FONT><BR></TH>
<TH style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;border-bottom:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></TH>
<TH ALIGN="LEFT" style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;border-bottom:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=1><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GUTTERGRID,"border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;border-bottom:solid #000000 1.0pt;" -->


 Performance Metric</B></FONT><BR></TH>
<TH style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;border-bottom:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></TH>
<TH ALIGN="CENTER" style="border-top:solid #000000 1.0pt;border-bottom:solid #000000 1.0pt;font-family:times;border-right:solid #000000 1.0pt;"><FONT SIZE=1><B>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>*</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Excludes
special items as detailed in Ford's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>**</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Market Share metric for each of the business units was based on a weighted average of the market share for each market within a particular business unit.
The Americas metric was based on 4&nbsp;markets; the Asia Pacific and Africa metric was based on 5&nbsp;markets; and the Europe metric was based on 19&nbsp;markets. The weightings for each
market within the business unit were based on the industry volumes of the markets within the relevant business unit.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>***</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Quality metrics for the relevant business units were developed from our Warranty Spending data and industry survey data that measured
Things-Gone-Wrong. To better understand the Quality metrics, we show the targets as the year-over-year improvement to be achieved. The actual targets
for the Things-Gone-Wrong metrics were the number of Things-Gone-Wrong for each relevant business unit and, in some cases, sub-business
units. The Warranty Spending targets had a similar design. Because showing the actual metrics would be unwieldy and not enhance your understanding of the target to be achieved, we have translated the
Things-Gone-Wrong and Warranty Spending targets into year-over-year improvement targets for each relevant business unit.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>****</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Corporate business unit did not have a formal target for the Market Share and Quality metrics. Instead, performance for the Corporate Market Share and
Quality metrics was a weighted average of the other business units' market share and quality performance. The weightings for Corporate Market Share and Quality metrics were as follows: The
Americas&nbsp;&#151; 67.7%; Ford of Europe&nbsp;&#151; 25.5%; and Asia Pacific and Africa&nbsp;&#151; 6.8%. These weightings were based on the planned net revenues of the
relevant business units for 2011. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The table below shows the total performance results for each of our business units. In order to increase our transparency, we chose to show results for our European business
unit because it impacts the results of the Corporate business unit. Based on the performance against each metric's targets within the relevant business unit shown above, the Committee calculated the
percent of the total target award earned for that business unit. </FONT></P>

 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee decided to pay out the Incentive Bonus Plan awards to the Named Executives according to the formula percentages in the table above (see column&nbsp;(g) of the Summary Compensation
Table on p.&nbsp;52). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Incremental Bonuses


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Our results relative to the 2011 Incentive Bonus Plan metrics represent continued progress toward our primary ONE Ford objective of becoming an exciting viable Ford delivering
profitable growth for all. This progress required exceptional performance by the Named Executives. In February 2012, the Committee created an individual performance fund which allows the Committee to
recognize and reward Named Executives with incremental bonuses beyond the Incentive Bonuses earned in a performance year (see column&nbsp;(d) of the Summary Compensation Table on p.&nbsp;52). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
maximum incremental bonus a Named Executive may be paid is 50% of the person's Incentive Bonus Award. The incremental bonus payout depends on the annual performance ratings for a Named Executive,
which depend upon the individual's performance against his or her personal objectives for the relevant year and his or her demonstration of the ONE Ford behaviors of: functional and technical
excellence; working together; role modeling Ford values; and delivering results. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each
of the Named Executives who received an incremental bonus played an integral role in the continued improvement in our balance sheet, global Automotive operating-related cash flow, and
profitability during 2011. In determining the incremental bonus to be awarded to each Named Executive the Committee considered the following factors: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Mulally
set the strategic direction and accelerated our ONE Ford Plan which significantly increased our Automotive operating-related cash flow and achieved our highest reported net income
in more than 10 years. Under Mr.&nbsp;Mulally's leadership, the Company also significantly reduced its debt and began paying a dividend to shareholders in the first quarter of 2012. Additionally, he
continued to sustain an environment of teamwork among the Company's senior leadership. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Ford
continued to provide leadership to ensure the Board of Directors sets Ford's strategic direction. He worked closely with Mr.&nbsp;Mulally to accelerate the restructuring of the
business to be profitable at lower volume and mix. Mr.&nbsp;Ford also continued to influence the Company's on-going work in the development and manufacture of alternative fuel vehicles.
He effectively communicated Ford's priorities with important constituencies, such as the media, dealers, and government officials. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Booth
provided leadership in strengthening our balance sheet and increased our net-cash position by $8.4&nbsp;billion at year-end 2011, to $9.8&nbsp;billion. He
led Company efforts to improve cash flow which resulted in positive rating </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>44</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=50,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=812274,FOLIO='44',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_45"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>agency
upgrades during the year so that our credit rating is now one level below investment grade. Mr.&nbsp;Booth also provided strategic direction for our Corporate and Ford Credit capital
improvement plans. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Fields
led our Americas operations to strong results again during 2011. He skillfully balanced operating and market factors to significantly exceed cash flow objectives for the year. Market
share improved in multiple markets and this was the first time since 1989 that U.S. market share increased three consecutive years. Mr.&nbsp;Fields's leadership in developing products our customers
want and value was key in the Company's 2011 performance. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs
led our Asia Pacific and Africa operations under extremely difficult circumstances. The Japanese earthquake and tsunami early in 2011 and the Thailand flooding later in the year
put extraordinary stress on that region's operations. Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs's leadership guided our business in Asia Pacific and Africa to significantly exceed quality metrics, mostly meet the cost
performance metric, and partially meet market share metrics. In light of the substantial headwinds the region faced, the Committee judged Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs's performance to be exceptional. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee recognized the above achievements of the Named Executives as supporting the four elements of our ONE Ford plan (see Executive Summary on p.&nbsp;33). In light of the achievements noted
above, the Committee determined that the performance of the Named Executives warranted additional recognition in the form of incremental bonuses. Because the incremental bonuses were paid outside of
the Incentive Bonus Plan, those payments are subject to the deduction limits of Code Section&nbsp;162(m) (see Tax Considerations on p.&nbsp;50). </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_equity-based_compensation"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_2"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Equity-Based Compensation


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Our equity-based incentive awards are tied to our performance and the future value of our common stock. These awards are intended to
focus executive behavior on our longer-term
interests, because today's business decisions affect Ford over a number of years. For 2011, our equity-based compensation consisted of annual grants of Performance Units, stock options, and
incremental incentive grants of Performance Units to certain Named Executives, as explained in more detail below. We understand that share-based compensation can be dilutive to shareholders. To
address this concern in 2012, we commenced a modest share repurchase program of common stock in order to offset the dilutive effect of share-based compensation. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
granting equity awards, the Committee determines a dollar value of equity awards to grant to each recipient. For officers, this dollar value is translated into a number of stock options based on a
Black-Scholes analysis and Performance Units based on the fair market value of Ford common stock on the date of grant. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>As
discussed above, the competitive survey indicates that equity-based compensation for the Named Executives is below the median of the comparator group on average, even when including the 2011
Incremental Incentive Grants. For Mr.&nbsp;Mulally, the survey showed that his total equity-based compensation was above the median of the survey group. Our 2011 equity-based compensation awards
reinforce our desire to, in general, pay at or near the median of equity compensation compared to the survey group as well as demonstrate flexibility in our compensation practices to reward superior
performance and to respond to changing business and economic conditions. Mr.&nbsp;Mulally's total equity-based compensation reflects his leadership responsibility for ONE Ford and the global Ford
enterprise and the Committee's desire to incentivize Mr.&nbsp;Mulally to increase shareholder value, thus aligning his interests with those of all shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Annual Performance Unit and Stock Option Grants


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Consistent with prior practice, the Committee continued the annual equity-based incentive program for the Named Executives by granting two types of equity-based compensation:
stock options and Performance Units (see Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2011 pp.&nbsp;55-56). The Committee awarded 50% of the value of each executive's annual equity award in stock options and 50%
in Performance Units. We believe this structure strikes the appropriate balance between driving executive behavior to accomplish annual business objectives while also focusing on
longer-term shareholder returns. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
stock options vest over three years, have a ten-year term, and function as our longest-term incentive. The Committee believes this focuses executive behavior and decision
making on our long-term interests and aligns the </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>45</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=51,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=584351,FOLIO='45',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_46"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>interests
of our executives with those of our shareholders. The Performance Units are earned, if at all, based on a one-year performance period, but are paid out in service-based
Restricted Stock Units, which vest over a two-year period. In granting the Performance Units, the Committee chose a one-year performance period in order to focus executive
behavior on achieving key short-term business objectives and to incentivize real-time continuous improvement of our performance. The two-year restriction period,
however, adds an intermediate element that serves to retain executives and focus their behavior beyond the initial one-year performance period. In addition, because executive decisions
regarding such matters as product development, marketing and sales, and the like, can affect our performance over several years, the Committee believes it is important to structure equity-based awards
so that executives will focus on the long-term impact of their decisions on the Company. This also further aligns executive interests with your interests as shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
general, the total value of these grants in 2011 was determined based on the following considerations:</FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>job responsibilities and expected role in our long-term performance; </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>retention needs; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>historical share allocations; </FONT><FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>the value of equity-based grants granted to the executive in the prior year; and </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>the total number of equity-based grants awarded to our employees. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
target awards for 2011 Performance Unit grants for the Named Executives are shown in column&nbsp;(h) of the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2011 Table on p.&nbsp;55. These amounts
also represent the maximum award
opportunity. Similar to the Incentive Bonus Plan, the Performance Unit formula has a sliding scale based on various levels of achievement for each metric. If minimum performance levels had not been
met for all metrics, the payout would have been zero. The Committee may decrease, but not increase, an award for Named Executives. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
disclosed in our 2011 CD&amp;A that, in order to further implement our ONE Ford Plan objective of working together effectively as one team, the Committee assigned all officers to the Corporate business
unit for purposes of the performance metrics under the 2011 annual Performance Unit grants. The Committee selected metrics, weightings, and targets identical to those under the 2011 Incentive Bonus
Plan (see Incentive Bonuses on pp.&nbsp;41-44), to emphasize the importance of our ONE Ford Plan objectives (see p.&nbsp;37). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
table below shows the performance results for each metric for the Corporate business unit and the total performance results against the metrics for 2011. The Committee reviewed Ford's performance
for 2011 against the goals. Based on this performance, the Committee determined the percentage of each of the five performance goals achieved and the percentage of the target award earned for the
Corporate business unit (see column&nbsp;(h) of Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2011 Table and footnote&nbsp;2 on p.&nbsp;55). </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_2011_performance_unit_performa__20102231"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_3"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  2011 Performance Unit Performance Results<BR>  (% of Target Achieved)


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>*The
Performance Results column for the Quality metric shows the combined percent achieved for the Things-Gone-Wrong target and Warranty Spending target, weighted equally as
shown in the 2011 Incentive Bonus Target and Performance Results Table on p.&nbsp;43. Although the performance results were less than 100%, our market share in the U.S. increased for the third
consecutive year for the first time since 1989. </FONT></P>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee decided to pay out at the levels earned in recognition of the following: (i)&nbsp;the Named Executives made substantial progress in accelerating our ONE Ford Plan; (ii)&nbsp;Final
Awards of Restricted Stock Units do not have an adverse impact on our cash flow in the current period; (iii)&nbsp;the two-year restriction period of the Restricted Stock </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>46</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=52,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=780103,FOLIO='46',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_47"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Units
serves as a retention tool; and (iv)&nbsp;the two-year restriction period focuses executive behavior on our longer-term interests. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2011 Incremental Incentive Grants


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Committee granted incremental Performance Units in March 2011 to certain executives, including Messrs.&nbsp;Mulally, Booth, Fields, and Hinrichs to provide a strong
incentive to further the ONE Ford Plan objective of restructuring our business to operate profitably at current demand and changing model mix. In structuring the grants, the Committee gave due
consideration to the competitive survey results that, in general, indicated the Named Executives were below the median of the survey group for equity awards. Mr.&nbsp;Mulally was included because
his leadership is essential to accomplishment of the metric. At his request, Mr.&nbsp;Ford did not receive a 2011 Incremental Incentive Grant. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
incremental grants of Performance Units have a two-year performance period. The performance metric is a reduction in global Ford brand platforms from 23&nbsp;platforms at the
beginning of 2011 to 19 by the end of 2012. Reducing the number of platforms enhances our cost competitiveness by reducing complexity and engineering costs. The maximum award is 100% of target. If the
reduction to 19&nbsp;platforms is not achieved, the payout will be zero. Final Awards, if any, will be paid out in time-based Restricted Stock Units that will have a two-year
restriction period. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Timing of Awards


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Annual grants of equity awards are typically determined at a February Compensation Committee meeting. At that time, data for previous performance periods are available to
determine the amount of the Final Awards. The Committee also decides the effective date of the Final Awards, and the annual equity-based grants of options and Performance Units. Due to administrative
complexity relating to valuation and notification, the Committee approved the annual 2012 equity-based grants on February&nbsp;21, 2012, and approved an effective date of March&nbsp;5, 2012. A
similar practice was also followed in previous years. The release of earnings information for the prior fiscal year is sufficiently in advance of the annual grant date for the public to be aware of
the information. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Committee does not time equity grant dates to affect the value of compensation either positively or negatively. Executive officers did not play a role in the selection of the grant dates. Special
grants, whether approved by the Compensation Committee for officers or the Long-Term Incentive Compensation Award Committee for non-officers, are effective either on a
specified future date (e.g., a date that coincides with a promotion or hiring date, or quarterly grant date), or the date of approval. In the case of an approval by written consent, the grant date
cannot be earlier than the date when the Committee member approvals have been obtained. See Corporate Governance&nbsp;&#151; Compensation Committee Operations at p.&nbsp;25 for more
information on the Long-Term Incentive Compensation Award Committee. For exercise prices of the 2011 option grants, see column&nbsp;(l) of the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in
2011 Table on p.&nbsp;55. Under the 2008 Plan, the terms of which were approved by you at the 2008 Annual Meeting, the exercise price of options will be the closing price of our common stock on the
date of grant. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_stock_ownership_goals"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_4"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Stock Ownership Goals


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In 1994, the Compensation Committee created stock ownership goals for executives at or above the Vice President level to further
align the interests of the executives with those of shareholders. The following table shows the officer level and respective ownership goal. </FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:70%;margin-left:15%;">

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" VALIGN="BOTTOM" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>500%</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<!-- end of user-specified TAGGED TABLE -->
 </DIV>
 <P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>47</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=53,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=499626,FOLIO='47',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_48"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Executives
have five years from taking their position to achieve their goal. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
review progress toward achievement of the ownership goals periodically. All forms of stock ownership&nbsp;&#151; including directly and indirectly owned shares of common stock, Final
Awards of Restricted Stock Units, and units that are based on common stock (excluding stock options and unearned Performance Units)&nbsp;&#151; count toward the goal. As of March&nbsp;5,
2012, all of the Named Executives comply with the stock ownership goals. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_compensation_programs_for_2012"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_5"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Compensation Programs for 2012


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We noted in Salaries on pp.&nbsp;40-41, that there were no annual merit increases to salaries for salaried employees in the U.S.
and Canada for 2011, including each of the Named Executives. Based on survey
data, we decided to implement modest annual merit increases to salary for our U.S. and Canadian salaried employees, including Messrs.&nbsp;Fields and Hinrichs, effective April 2012. Mr.&nbsp;Ford
and Mr.&nbsp;Mulally did not receive merit increases. Mr.&nbsp;Booth retired effective April&nbsp;1, 2012. In addition, effective July&nbsp;1 we will increase the Company-match for our
salaried 401(k) plan from $.60 to $.80 per dollar of employee contributions up to 5&nbsp;percent of the employee's base salary. Again, survey data indicated that this increase in Company-matching
contributions would bring our plan to a more competitive level. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>At
the 2011 Annual Meeting, we asked shareholders to approve the compensation of the Named Executives as presented in our 2011 Proxy Statement. You approved the compensation of the Named Executives
with 93.4% of votes cast "For" approval. Based on this result, the Committee decided not to make any significant changes to the compensation programs of the Named Executives for 2011 and 2012.
Additionally, we asked shareholders whether the frequency of the vote to approve the compensation of the Named Executives should occur every one, two, or three years. You agreed with our
recommendation to have an annual vote to approve the compensation of the Named Executives with 95.4% of votes cast in favor of an annual vote. The Board of Directors adopted the policy of submitting
for approval the compensation of the Named Executives as disclosed in the Company's proxy statements to an annual vote (see Proposal&nbsp;3 on pp.&nbsp;69-70.) </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Beginning
with the 2012 performance year, all Incentive Bonus Plan eligible employees will be measured against performance-to-metrics on a single set of corporate metrics. Consequently, we are
eliminating the metrics related to the three regional business units (Americas, Europe, and Asia Pacific and Africa) for Incentive Bonus Plan purposes. We believe this reinforces the ONE Ford Plan of
a lean global enterprise and recognizes the regional trade-offs that are frequently required to ensure overall corporate success on profit before taxes, Automotive operating-related cash flow, cost
performance, market share, and quality. The weightings for the metrics remain unchanged. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_retirement_plans"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_6"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Retirement Plans


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In general, we believe that the retirement plans described below serve several worthwhile business purposes, including retaining top
leadership talent. In addition, they provide income security to long serving executives, and provide flexibility to us in transferring executives among our operations. We believe these programs to be
reasonable and appropriate in light of competitive practices and our executives' total compensation program. For additional information, see the Pension Benefits in 2011 Table on p.&nbsp;61 and the
Nonqualified Deferred Compensation in 2011 Table on p.&nbsp;63. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pre-2004 Plans


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Our General Retirement Plan ("GRP") provides a tax-qualified benefit for each year of non-contributory participation by employees in the U.S. hired
before January&nbsp;1, 2004, and added benefits for those who make contributions. We also have two other non-qualified retirement plans for certain employees: the Supplemental Executive
Retirement Plan ("SERP") that provides a supplemental monthly benefit calculated on a percentage of final average pay and service, and the Benefit Equalization Plan ("GRP-BEP"). Under the
GRP-BEP, eligible employees receive benefits substantially equal to those they could have received under the GRP but were not able to because of Internal Revenue Code limitations.
Messrs.&nbsp;Booth, Ford, Fields, and Hinrichs are eligible for benefits under the GRP, SERP, and GRP-BEP. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>48</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=54,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=389629,FOLIO='48',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_49"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Certain
eligible executives who separate from employment after age 55 (age 52 if retiring under our Select Retirement Plan ("SRP")) and prior to age 65 may be eligible for monthly benefits under our
Executive Separation Allowance Plan ("ESAP") that provides a percentage of salary, based on age and service, at time of separation until age 65. The SRP is a voluntary retirement program offered from
time-to-time for select U.S. management employees. In 2006 the Committee requested that its consultant, Semler Brossy Consulting Group, LLC, and the Company jointly conduct a
review of the SRP as a severance vehicle. The review compared present values of the SRP benefit with traditional severance packages, examined potential changes, and considered benefits to the Company
and to executives. The Committee reviewed the report and concluded that the SRP should remain in its current form to facilitate the reduction in workforce then being undertaken by the Company and to
provide flexibility to accommodate any future reductions. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Benefits
under SERP, SRP, ESAP, and GRP-BEP are not funded. In addition, in accordance with Code Section&nbsp;409A, benefits that accrued or vested on or after January&nbsp;1, 2005
under these plans may not be paid to certain key executives until at least six months following their separation from employment. Each of these plans had been amended in order to provide
Mr.&nbsp;Ford with benefits using a notional base annual salary during the period he did not receive a cash salary (i.e., November 2001 through July 2010). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Post-January&nbsp;1, 2004 Plan


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


 </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Consistent with our Strategy Statement (see Compensation Philosophy, Strategy, and Guiding Principles on pp.&nbsp;35-36) to develop benefit programs that provide employees
with income security and protection from catastrophic loss while minimizing our long-term liabilities, Ford adopted a tax qualified retirement plan, the Ford Retirement Plan ("FRP"), for
salaried employees hired or rehired on or after January&nbsp;1, 2004 in the U.S. The FRP was adopted in order to provide us with more predictable retirement benefit costs and reduced financial
statement volatility. These goals are achieved through a stable contribution schedule and the transfer of financial and demographic risks from us to plan participants while still providing employees
with the opportunity for adequate income in retirement. Employees who participate in this plan, including Mr.&nbsp;Mulally, are not eligible to participate in the GRP (with respect to future
service), GRP-BEP, SERP, or ESAP. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_other_benefits_and_perquisites"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_7"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Other Benefits and Perquisites


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>We provided certain perquisites and other benefits to senior management in 2011, the most significant of which are summarized below.
The Committee periodically reviews our policies on perquisites and other benefits. The cost of these perquisites and other benefits are included in column&nbsp;(i) of the Summary Compensation Table
on p.&nbsp;52. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Personal Travel:</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As part of our efforts to reduce costs and conserve cash, we decided to close our Air Transportation operation in 2008. Company policy does not
allow Messrs.&nbsp;Mulally or Ford to fly commercially due to security concerns. Consequently, the Company pays the charter costs of their use of private aircraft for business and personal travel.
The families of Messrs.&nbsp;Mulally and Ford are allowed to accompany them on trips when they travel on private aircraft. In addition, the Company will pay the cost of coach-class commercial
aircraft flights for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally's family when their travel is at his request. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Requiring
Messrs.&nbsp;Mulally and Ford to use private aircraft for all travel provides several benefits to Ford. First, the policy is intended to ensure the personal safety of our President and CEO
and our Executive Chairman, both of whom maintain significant public roles for Ford. Second, use of private aircraft ensures their availability and maximizes the time available for Ford business. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
retention purposes, the Company continues to pay the costs, including first class commercial airfare, for personal travel for Mr.&nbsp;Fields to and from his residences. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Evaluation Vehicle Program:</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We maintain a program that provides our officers with the use of two Company vehicles free of charge. This program requires officers to
provide written evaluations on a variety of our vehicles, providing important feedback on the design and quality of our products. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>49</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=55,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=1033697,FOLIO='49',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DQ47101A.;17',USER='EYOUNG',CD='21-MAR-2012;08:46' -->
<A NAME="page_dq47101_1_50"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Other Services:</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For certain executive officers, including the Named Executives, we provide a home security evaluation and security system. We also provide an
allowance to senior managers for financial counseling services and estate planning. We pay for approximately 75% of the cost of this service up to $7,500. The safety and security (personal and
financial) of our executives is critically important. We believe the benefits of providing these programs outweigh the relatively minor costs associated with them. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><B> Tax Reimbursement:</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As noted in our 2011 CD&amp;A, the Committee decided to eliminate tax gross-ups for executive perquisites. As part of the Company's
temporary living/relocation policy, however, the Company provides tax reimbursement for all levels of employees who relocate at the Company's request. The Committee believes that not reimbursing taxes
for employees who move at the Company's request is an unfair financial burden. This policy also allows executives to gain experience in a variety of our world-wide operations. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_alan_mulally"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_8"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Alan Mulally


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Effective September&nbsp;1, 2006, we entered into an agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Mulally relating to his hiring as President and
Chief Executive Officer. That agreement contained a "change in control" provision that expired on August&nbsp;31, 2011. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
September 2008, the Committee decided to continue indefinitely the arrangement of providing housing in Dearborn, Michigan to Mr.&nbsp;Mulally. The Committee believes the arrangement is beneficial
to Mr.&nbsp;Mulally and the
Company by allowing him to continue to focus on our ONE Ford Plan. The cost of this benefit is included in column&nbsp;(i) of the Summary Compensation Table on p.&nbsp;52; however, beginning in
2011 we no longer provide tax gross-up for this arrangement. He is eligible for relocation assistance pursuant to our relocation program if he chooses to relocate his household. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_tax_considerations"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_9"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=3><B>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Tax Considerations


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dq47101_internal_revenue_code__sect;_162(m)"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dq47101_10"> </A></FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><B><I>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Internal Revenue Code &sect;&nbsp;162(m)


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


    <BR>    </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Code Section&nbsp;162(m) generally disallows Federal tax deductions for compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to the Chief Executive
Officer and the next three highest paid officers (other than the Chief Financial Officer) whose compensation is required to be reported in the Summary Compensation Table of the proxy statement
("Covered Executives"). Certain performance-based compensation is not subject to this deduction limitation. In our case, this exemption applies to certain awards under the Incentive Bonus Plan and the
2008 Plan. Specifically, Incentive Bonus Plan payments made for 2011 performance, 2011 awards of stock options, and Final Awards related to Performance Units were not subject to the deduction limit.
However, the incremental bonuses paid to the Named Executives (see column&nbsp;(d) of the Summary Compensation Table on p.&nbsp;52) are subject to the deduction limit. Additionally, we cannot
deduct that portion of any Covered Executive's salary that is in excess of $1&nbsp;million, or the cost of any perquisites provided to a Covered Executive whose salary exceeds $1&nbsp;million. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Generally,
we strive to maximize the tax deductibility of our compensation arrangements. In the highly competitive market for talent, however, we believe the Committee needs flexibility in designing
compensation that will attract and retain talented executives and provide special incentives to promote various corporate objectives. The Committee, therefore, retains discretion to award compensation
that is not fully tax deductible. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>50</FONT></P>

<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Compensation Committee Report


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis (CD&amp;A) with management. Based on this
review and discussion, the Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the CD&amp;A be included in this Proxy Statement and incorporated by reference into our annual report on
Form&nbsp;10-K. </FONT></P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TF,"font-family:ARIAL;" --><font style="font-family:ARIAL;">


  Compensation of Executive Officers


</font><!-- COMMAND=ADD_ETF,"A" -->


  <BR>  </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The table below shows the before-tax compensation for Alan Mulally, who served as President and CEO during 2011,
L.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;K.&nbsp;Booth, who served as Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer during 2011, and the three most highly compensated executive officers at the end of 2011. </FONT></P>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(1)</SUP>As
noted in the 2011 Compensation Discussion and Analysis, Mr.&nbsp;Ford's 2010 compensation included prior years' compensation that was earned and paid when the Committee
determined in August 2010 that the Company's global Automotive sector had achieved full-year profitability, excluding special items. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(2)</SUP>The
amounts shown for 2010 reflect discretionary bonus awards paid in 2011 for 2010 performance and amounts shown for 2011 reflect discretionary bonus awards paid in 2012 for 2011
performance (see "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Annual Compensation&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Incremental Bonuses" on pp.&nbsp;44-45). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(3)</SUP>The
amounts shown in columns&nbsp;(e) and (f) reflect the aggregate grant date value computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic&nbsp;718 for stock-based and option awards for each
of the Named Executives for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2009, 2010, and 2011. The assumptions used for the 2011, 2010, and 2009 calculations can be found at footnote&nbsp;20 to our audited
financial statements in Ford's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 and footnote&nbsp;21 to our audited financial statements in Ford's Annual
Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2010 and December&nbsp;31, 2009. Pursuant to SEC rules, we disregarded the estimate of forfeitures related to
service-based vesting conditions. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Included
in the amounts shown in column&nbsp;(e) are the grant date values of certain awards that are subject to performance conditions. Pursuant to SEC rules, the grant date values shown above are
reported based upon the </FONT></P>

amounts shown in column&nbsp;(g) reflect awards earned by certain Named Executives under the Incentive Bonus Plan (see "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151;
Annual Compensation&nbsp;&#151; B.&nbsp;Incentive Bonuses" on pp.&nbsp;41-44). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(5)</SUP>The
amounts shown reflect the increase in the actuarial present value of accrued pension benefits under various Company plans. For 2011 the accrued pension benefits are measured from
December&nbsp;31, 2010 to December&nbsp;31, 2011; for 2010, the accrued pension benefits are measured from December&nbsp;31, 2009 to December&nbsp;31, 2010; and for 2009, the accrued pension
benefits are measured from December&nbsp;31, 2008 to December&nbsp;31, 2009. See the Pension Benefits in 2011 Table and related footnotes on pp.&nbsp;61-63 for additional information, including
the present value assumptions used in these calculations. No Named Executive received preferential or above-market earnings on deferred compensation. </FONT></P>

 </DIV>
<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(i)</SUP>For
a description of perquisites relating to personal use of private aircraft, our evaluation vehicle program, and security and other services for Named Executives, see "Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151;&nbsp;Other Benefits and Perquisites" on pp.&nbsp;49-50. Other perquisites and personal benefits whose incremental cost is included in the
amounts shown consist of the following: personal use of Company phone cards and cell phones, personal use of car and driver service, annual executive health exams, ground transportation services,
regulatory filing fees, fuel and car washes related to the evaluation vehicles, and temporary housing and relocation expenses. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Executives
also may make personal use of Company season tickets to athletic events, but such use does not result in incremental cost to the Company because the tickets are for business use and when
the executive uses them for personal use, the executive pays for any additional costs associated with personal use. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>Amounts
for the Named Executives include the incremental costs to the Company for providing certain perquisites and other benefits during 2011. For Mr.&nbsp;Mulally, the amount shown includes
$178,571 for personal use of private aircraft, $59,907 for security, and $89,277 for housing and living expenses. For Mr.&nbsp;Ford, the amount shown includes $259,666 for personal use of aircraft
and $913,907 for security. For Mr.&nbsp;Fields, the amount shown includes $39,755 as the actual cost of first class commercial airfare for personal travel to and from his residences. For
Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs, the amount shown includes $163,940 as the actual cost of benefits related to his international service relocation. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>During
2011, for use of private aircraft, we used the actual costs incurred for leasing private aircraft. We calculated the aggregate incremental cost of security and housing expenses as the actual
cost incurred to provide these benefits. We calculated the aggregate incremental cost of providing the evaluation vehicles by estimating the lease fee for a comparable vehicle under our Management
Lease Program. The lease fee under that program takes into account the cost of using the vehicle, maintenance, license, title and registration fees, and insurance. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(ii)</SUP>Effective
January&nbsp;1, 2011, we no longer provide tax reimbursement for executive perquisites; however, tax reimbursement is provided on imputed income related to relocation
benefits for employees who relocate at the Company's request (see "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Other Benefits and Perquisites" on pp.&nbsp;49-50). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(iii)</SUP>Amounts
shown reflect the dollar value of premiums paid by the Company for life insurance in an amount equal to 3 times an employee's salary. Employees may purchase additional life
insurance and these premiums are payroll deducted with no additional Company contributions or cost. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(iv)</SUP>The
amount shown for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally reflects contributions made to his Ford Retirement Plan account (see "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Retirement
Plans" on pp.&nbsp;48-49) and Company matching contributions to his 401(k) account. The amounts for the other Named Executives reflect Company matching contributions to employee 401(k) accounts. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(v)</SUP>The
amount shown for Mr.&nbsp;Mulally primarily reflects Company contributions to a nonqualified benefit equalization plan related to the Ford Retirement Plan and the Company's
401(k) plan. The amounts shown for Messrs.&nbsp;Booth, </FONT></P>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>54</FONT></P>

Ford, Fields, and Hinrichs reflect contributions made to a nonqualified benefit equalization plan related to the Company's 401(k) plan (see Nonqualified Deferred Compensation in 2011 Table and
footnotes 1 and 2 on pp.&nbsp;63-64). Furthermore, the amounts shown for Messrs.&nbsp;Booth and Hinrichs include income tax preparation fees related to international assignments and, for
Mr.&nbsp;Hinrichs, various payments related to his international service assignment, such as cost-of-living adjustments and settling-in allowance. These benefits
are generally available to any level of employee who is on an international assignment. </FONT></P>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(1)</SUP>The
amounts shown in columns&nbsp;(e) and (f) represent the target and maximum amounts payable for 2011 performance under the Incentive Bonus Plan. Our Incentive Bonus Plan does not
have a formal threshold award in that there is no minimum amount payable for a certain level of performance under the plan. The Compensation Committee
exercises discretion as to whether to make payouts if performance does not achieve target levels. The material terms of the awards are described in "Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Annual Compensation&nbsp;&#151; B.&nbsp;Incentive Bonuses" at pp.&nbsp;41-44. For awards made under the Incentive Bonus Plan for 2011 performance, see
column&nbsp;(g) of the Summary Compensation Table on p.&nbsp;52. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(2)</SUP>For
each of the Named Executives the amounts shown in column&nbsp;(h) consist of the following grants: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(i)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
first line of column&nbsp;(h) consists of annual grants of Performance Units that provided an opportunity to earn a Final Award of Restricted Stock
Units for 2011 performance. The amounts shown represent the target amount of the opportunity. 2011 performance was measured against the metrics and weightings discussed in "Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Equity-Based Compensation&nbsp;&#151; A.&nbsp;Annual Performance Unit and Stock Option Grants" on pp.&nbsp;45-47. The Restricted Stock Units earned for 2011
performance have a two-year restriction period and will not pay Dividend Equivalents during the restriction period. Following the restriction period, shares of Ford common stock will be
issued, less shares withheld for tax withholding. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
 </DIV>
 <P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>55</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=61,EFW="2208104",CP="FORD MOTOR COMPANY",DN="1",CHK=979471,FOLIO='55',FILE='DISK112:[12ZAF1.12ZAF47101]DU47101A.;52',USER='EYOUNG',CD='26-MAR-2012;08:06' -->
<A NAME="page_du47101_1_56"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg47101a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(ii)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
second line of column&nbsp;(h) consists of grants of Performance Units that provide an opportunity to earn a Final Award of Restricted Stock Units
for 2011-2012 performance. The amount shown represents the target amount of the opportunity. These grants were made pursuant to the 2011 Incremental Incentive Grants and have a two-year
performance period and Final Awards, if any, will be made in March 2013 (see "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Equity Compensation&nbsp;&#151; B.&nbsp;2011
Incremental Incentive Grants" on p.&nbsp;47). Final Awards will be made in Restricted Stock Units with a two-year restriction period and will not pay Dividend Equivalents during the
restriction period. Following the restriction period, shares of Ford common stock will be issued, less shares withheld for tax withholding. Mr.&nbsp;Ford did not participate in the 2011 Incremental
Incentive Grants. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(3)</SUP>The
amounts shown in column&nbsp;(k) represent 10-year stock option grants. In general, 33% of each stock option grant vests one year after the grant date, 33% after two
years, and 34% after three years. Any unexercised options expire after ten years. If a grantee retires, becomes disabled, or dies, his or her options continue to be exercisable up to the normal
expiration date. In most other instances of employment termination, all options generally end upon termination of employment or are exercisable for a specified period. Options are subject to certain
conditions, including not engaging in competitive activity. Options generally cannot be transferred except through inheritance. In general, each grantee agrees to remain a Ford employee for at least
one year from the date of the option grant. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(4)</SUP>The
exercise price of the options is the closing price of Ford common stock traded on the NYSE on the effective date of the grant (see "Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Equity-Based Compensation&nbsp;&#151; C.&nbsp;Timing of Awards" on p.&nbsp;47). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(5)</SUP>The
amounts shown in column&nbsp;(m) represent the full grant date value of each equity-based award shown in the table for each Named Executive computed under FASB ASC
Topic&nbsp;718. For awards subject to performance conditions, the values shown are based upon the probable outcome of such conditions as of the grant date. </FONT></P>
 </DIV>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <P style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>(1)</SUP>The table below details the vesting schedule for stock option grants based on the termination date of the relevant grant. In general, option
grants vest 33% one year after the grant date, 33% two years after the grant date, and 34% three years after the grant date. </FONT></P>
 </DIV>
<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:70%;margin-left:15%;">
